06363nam a22007815i 9781477306642DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211967txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773066427 a10.7560/7366582doi  a(DE-B1597)587115  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1434b.L564 1967eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a970.4200aHandbook of Middle American Indians, Volume 5 :bLinguistics /ced. by Norman A. McQuown, Robert Wauchope. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1967  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- t1. History of Studies in Middle American Linguistics -- t2. Inventory of Descriptive Materials -- t3. Inventory of Classificatory Materials -- t4. Lexicostatistic Classification -- t5. Systemic Comparison and Reconstruction -- t6. Environmental Correlational Studies -- t7. Type Linguistic Descriptions -- tA. Classical Nahuatl -- tB. Classical Yucatec (Maya) -- tC. Classical Quiche -- tD. Sierra Popoluca -- tE. Isthmus Zapotec -- tF. Huautla de Jiménez Mazatec -- tG. Jiliapan Pame -- tH. Huamelultec Chontal -- t8. Language-in-Culture Studies -- tReferences0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume, the fifth in the Handbook of Middle American Indians, presents a summary of work accomplished since the Spanish conquest in the contemporary description and historical reconstruction of the indigenous languages and language families of Mexico and Central America. The essays include the following: “Inventory of Descriptive Materials” by William Bright; “Inventory of Classificatory Materials” by Maria Teresa Fernández de Miranda, “Lexicostatistic Classification” by Morris Swadesh, “Systemic Comparison and Reconstruction” by Robert Longacre, and “Environmental Correlational Studies” by Sarah C. Gudschinsky. Sketches of Classical Nahuatl by Stanley Newman, Classical Yucatec Maya by Norman A. McQuown, and Classical Quiché by Munro S. Edmonson provide working tools for tackling the voluminous early postconquest texts in these languages of late preconquest empires (Aztec, Maya, Quiché). Further sketches of Sierra Popoluca by Benjamin F. Elson, of Isthmus Zapotec by Velma B. Pickett, of Huautla de Jiménez Mazatec by Eunice V. Pike, of Jiliapan Pame by Leonardo Manrique C., and of Huamelultec Chontal by Viola Waterhouse—together with those of Nahuatl, Maya, and Quiché—provide not only descriptive outlines of as many different linguistic structures but also linguistic representatives of seven structurally different families of Middle American languages. Miguel Léon-Portilla presents an outline of the relations between language and the culture of which it is a part and provides examples of some of these relations as revealed by contemporary research in indigenous Middle America. The volume editor, Norman A. McQuown (1914–2005), was Professor of Anthropology at The University of Chicago. He formerly taught at Hunter College and served with the Mexican Department of Indian Affairs. He carried out fieldwork with Totonac, Huastec, Tzeltal-Tzotzil, Mame, and other tribes. The Handbook of Middle American Indians was assembled and edited at the Middle American Research Institute of Tulane University with the assistance of grants from the National Science Foundation and under the sponsorship of the National Research Council Committee on Latin American Anthropology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBright, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdmonson, Munro S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElson, Benjamin F., econtributor.4ctb4h